title: For Sale/Trade:  Antique .32 ACP aka 7.65 Browning Revolver WTT for cheap 12ga or small pistol
postcontent: From the internet research I've done this is a 1930's .32ACP/7.65 Browning chambered revolver.  Either German or Belgian made and 5 rd capacity. Pocket sized with upward folding trigger.I bought this gun (the .32) at an antique gun show and thought that it was a really neat gun.  The seller did not reveal at time of purchase that the gun needs some work to be fully functional.I knew that the safety was missing, and could tell that the firing pin was not the original and someone had made it themself.  The biggest issue is that the piece which should hold the bullet revolver in place after rotating is missing.  After I tried firing it for the first time, the firing pin moved backwards.My grandfather tried to help me fix the firing pin in place with a torch and some solder, however this did not completely fix the problem.I have fired a couple of rounds with it, but not by pulling the trigger.  I was able to fire the primer manually by using my thumb to pull the hammer back further than the trigger and release it.  This struck the primer with enough force to fire a round.One of the plastic grips has a small chip missing.  Both sides have a pretty neat relief of a head (similar to a coin).It's still a really neat looking antique and with some restoration would be an awesome piece.  Even without restoration it is a unique antique with a cool look.I am giving full disclosure (unlike the original seller).I'm looking to get $100 or best offer (or trade for a shotgun or other small handgun).  Will include a mostly full box of Browning 7.65 Auto (aka .32 ACP).I'm especially interested in a 12 gauge of some sort just for home defense(prefer pump, but would consider semi-auto, single, or double barrel), mainly bc I already have some sub lethal shells and bird loads in 12ga, but shoot me an offer with anything.  Even if it's a really crappy 12ga I don't care as long as it's functional.  I'm even interested in other shotguns or rifles, too, but must be functional and preferably include at least a little ammo, but ammo not a deal breaker.This pistol is interesting as a conversation piece if nothing else.  I would love to trade this ASAP.  I'm also very interested in a trade for a small handgun of some sort.  Please make me an offer.  Motivated seller!

title: For Sale/Trade:  Rock Island 22TCM/9mm 17+1
postcontent: Up for TRADE or sale, I have a Rock Island Combination Pistol.  It is a 1911A2 in 9mm for fun, practice, watermelon exploding, allowing your brother-in-law to shoot the cheap ammunition, etc and 22TCM for having real fun.  Those of you who are familiar with the cartridge know that it Barks like a Big Dog, but kicks like a kitten.  The energy it transfers to its target is akin to that of a .44 Magnum while you are not limited to 6 rounds and don't develop the "Magnumitis" that is associated with high recoil calibers.  If you are unfamiliar with the caliber, I will be happy to discuss it with you or, since I am obviously biased, I can point you in the direction of discussion fora (apparently, that's the correct plural form of the Latin word "Forum").  If you read the fora, please look carefully at the points of view of the writers.  Many critics will have never fired the cartridge.  (there will also be a lot of cheerleaders who've never fired it either)  The only valid point of view will come from one who has fired the round.  It has been my observation, that most who have fired it love it.  Most of all, I would like to find someone who purchased a model of the same gun with 10+1 round capacity and an accessory rail.  I am willing to trade my pistol (with case, both barrels, etc) and 100 rounds of ammo for a 10+1 model and $250 cash.  Anybody who has one of these guns knows how much the ammunition costs when you can find it.  If you don't have a 10+1 model to trade, the price is $575 for the used gun.  The ammo is $25/box of 50 rounds (I have more than 2 boxes if you need some, but the primary purpose of this ad is not to sell ammo).  This may seem high, but it is less than you'll pay at Cabela's. You also won't pay tax or shipping.  These are the 22TCM, not the 22TCM-R. They will not fit the pistols (Glock, EAA) that were retrofitted for it.If there seems to be the beginning of something we could work into a deal here, please help an injured (I dislike the label "Disabled") vet, get in touch.  We'll see if we can find some middle ground.   It's a special gun that you can't always find.  Before (the very day before) I bought the 17+1 version, I had bought the 10+1 version.  On impulse, I sold the 10+1 on the way to meet the guy who sold me the 17+1.  A long time ago, A number of years ago, my right hand was slamed in the turret of a hmmwv. The army tried to fix it a couple of times, but to no avail.  As a result, my injured right hand cannot grip the wide grip on the hi-cap version.  I wish I had the standard capacity back.  That is the objective here.You'll be helping out a veteran who is recovering from cancer and has 3 kids, 2 of which are in college.  I am fortunate enough to have kids who like to come out and shoot as a family related passtime.  As we all know, the family that plays together and prays together, stays together.  I whink we're doing pretty well on those fronts.  If you cansee to your own family's fun with this gun and help us out, it will be appreciated.
